Appendix A: Homemade "Mock" Clotted Cream
Real Cornish Clotted Cream is a protected product requiring unpasteurized milk and specific heating cycles. However, standard US whipped cream is too airy and light to stand up to the dense texture of Summer Pudding. This "Mock" recipe replicates the mouthfeel and density of clotted cream.
Ingredients:
4 oz Mascarpone Cheese (room temp)
1 cup Heavy Whipping Cream (cold)
1 tbsp Confectioners' Sugar
1/2 tsp Vanilla Bean Paste
Method:
In a chilled bowl, beat the mascarpone and sugar until smooth.
Slowly stream in the heavy cream while whipping.
Whip until the mixture holds stiff, dense peaks. Do not over-whip to butter.
Chill for 1 hour before serving. The mascarpone provides the "clotted" density and richness that pairs perfectly with the acidic pudding.32
Conclusion
The "Master" Summer Pudding is a dish of deceptive simplicity. It requires no oven, no gelatin, and no custard powders. Yet, it demands a rigorous understanding of its materials. By respecting the retrogradation of starch, the pectin content of currants, and the physics of hydraulic pressure, the home cook can elevate this rustic Victorian health food into a world-class dessert. The result is not just a pudding, but a celebration of the essence of summer fruit—captured, compressed, and presented in its most intensified form.
